# Dependencies
node_modules/

# Environment files
.env
.env.local
.env.development
.env.production
.env*.local

# Frontend build output
frontend/dist
frontend/.next
frontend/out

# Backend logs
backend/logs
*.log

# OS files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# IDE files
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo

# Debug
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*

# Uploads (if you store user uploads locally)
backend/uploads/*
!backend/uploads/.gitkeep

# Coverage
coverage/
```

One root `.gitignore` handles everything since patterns like `node_modules/` and `.env` apply recursively to all subfolders. So it catches `frontend/node_modules`, `backend/node_modules`, `frontend/.env`, `backend/.env` — all with one file.

**Your final folder structure should look like:**
```
linkedin-app/
├── .gitignore          ← this file
├── README.md
├── frontend/
│   ├── .env            ← frontend env (git ignored)
│   ├── package.json
│   └── src/
└── backend/
    ├── .env            ← backend env (git ignored)
    ├── package.json
    └── server.js
```

**One important thing** — create a `.env.example` file in both frontend and backend folders with dummy values. This way anyone cloning your repo knows what variables they need:

**frontend/.env.example**
```
VITE_API_URL=http://localhost:5000/api
```

**backend/.env.example**
```
PORT=5000
DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=3306
DB_USER=root
DB_PASSWORD=your_password
DB_NAME=linkedin_app
JWT_SECRET=your_secret_key